details: It is a Skype meeting and all behavior questions. In the very end I asked "It seems a lot companies ask very technical questions but why Dell do this differently?" He answered "Since the technology changing very fast, and you GPA seems fine, so we did not ask for that".
questions: What is your past project?
Do you like teamwork and how to overcome disagreement during teamwork?
Why do you apply Dell?

details: Very quick interview. Interviewers were nice but hard to read. I don't believe they thought I was a good candidate from the start but I currently have no idea how the interview actually went.
questions: Favorite sorting algorithm?

details: Mainly behavioral. The interviewer asked me to code a simple program and then asked mainly about my undergraduate coursework and projects. He also asked some basic aptitude and logical questions which I answered correctly. It was a good interview but later they messaged me saying that there were no positions open as of now (which I found a bit strange).
questions: Nothing specific. Asked me which software languages had I worked on and what courses have you taken.

details: Invited to interview after attending speaking to a recruiter during my university career fair. I interviewed on my school's campus the following day and received an offer later that afternoon. Very quick process.
questions: Tell me about one of your project experiences from your resume.

details: Campus interview, applied through university career center.The interviewer was kind and patient. We talked about my past projects and he also asked some design pattern question. I think I did a good job but no response after the interview even though I emailed the recruiter twice. After 2 months, I received a short email saying they would not move forward my candidacy.
questions: past project, design pattern

details: Apply on Dell job, had a on campus interview. Two engineering managers asked me questions about my project. Interviewing with Dell is honestly the best interview experience I've ever had. Much better than Google, Microsoft. The people who interviewed me made me feel like they really care, and they are actually trying to see if I am a good fit for a job in Dell. Overall it's a great experience
questions: Nothing special, very easy question

details: I was asked for technical interviews with two different groups, no HR part involved so far. Applied through university. Interview invitation sent by email. We got a free dinner (dell networking event) the night before interview day.
questions: Basic data structure, string manipulation, pointers. Since I learned about these during freshmen year, I pretty much forgot most of these when I was interviewed. I didn't review because I thought first round should be HR, but I was wrong...

details: The whole process takes an awful lot of time! 5 weeks and then a generic message saying it will take longer. Interview questions are easy. 2:1 for full time positions. There was a networking event the night before the interview was scheduled. Felt good to meet with the recruiters and talk to them about their experience working at Dell.
questions: Mostly behavioral questions. The technical questions were related to data structures

details: Applied with my resume through the career center of my school. I honestly did expect they were going to call me, however somehow got an interview a or so week later. The interview took place at my University and was about 30 min. all technical questions. After that I received an offer a few weeks later.
questions: Simple data structures questions (diff. between stack and a queue) and questions about my school projects

details: Was flown in for college interviews along with 50 or so other people. First we were taken out on the town and treated to dinner. We spent the night on the Hyatt by the river, which was nice.On the day of the interview, we first talked to the HR recruiter, then we were interviewed in a large room where there were many hiring managers present. What happened next was very…  similar to speed dating.Each interviewee had an assigned seat, where they were interviewed by their assigned potential manager to be. Every 30 minutes, the managers would all rotate seats (musical chairs style) and talk to their next potential candidate.Each manager had hiring authority, so if one guy liked you, you were in. I had 3 interviews that day, so in theory could have gotten 3 separate offers.
questions: The manager that hired me just wanted to know what I like to do on the weekends b/c my resume already showed that I had technical knowledge. Other managers asked me to tell them everything I knew about BIOS programming, which was zero.

details: one phone interview asking all the details on the resume.get response inviting for onsite in one week.On site interview:interviewed with five engineers. All technical questions. not so difficult.
questions: Linux kernel details

details: The interview process was lengthy and thorough. Interviews with several managers and technical leads. Asked questions about my experience and expertise. Met individually with each person on the interview panel. Some of the questions were very technical and some were just general interview questions on work experience and past employers.
questions: What types of debug tools have you used?

details: I was interviewed by an older hiring manager. The only thing resembling a technical interview was him asking me to rate myself on various programming languages. He then spent the rest of the time talking about how he was overbooked for the day and that he had lunch in my hometown once.
questions: Rate yourself from 1-10 on <insert programming language>?

details: Was asked about previous work experience, about the details of the previous projects. Then was asked some general questions about object-oriented design and principles. Also, had several questions about algorithms and data structures, was asked about implementation of various trees. Then was asked about software development lifecycle.
questions: Object-oriented design
Algorithms and data structures

details: I received a call for a phone screen 3-days after posting to a position. The manager did a skills interview and a review of the position. A week later a group interview was scheduled. First couple of interviewers were standard, with no goofy questions. The third interviewer was from another department that had absolutely no involvement with the group I was interviewing for, and he had no questions for me.…  I questioned him about his position and how this group would help his group, but he had no feedback. We spoke about the company culture and wrapped up the whole thing in 10 minutes. The third person would have been a peer. His stated concern was that this position was created to eliminate other positions in the department.
questions: So you are here to eliminate our jobs?
I don't work with these guys and have no idea what I am doing in this interview, so I don't have any questions for you.

details: Was invited to on-site interview by a Recruiter.Got a paper exam on-site. I received an exam with no coding questions, only ordinary object oriented definition questions. Was asked about common data structure and design pattern. Included also theoretical multithreaded questions.Was told that my exam wil be revised together with other candidates answers and the best will be invited to the next round.
questions: Describe composite design pattern

details: 4 rounds of interview two technical round ( telephonic & F2F), third is the Managerial and fourth is the Hr for salary negotiation and told offer letter will be rolled out in 2-3 days, after that they didn't turned simply waste of time,The whole interview process took 3 weeks.
questions: Questions related to your resume

details: This was a phone screening interview - the first stage in interview process. I was told that if I passed this stage than I would be called in for a face to face interview. I will know within a week if I have an opportunity to progress.

details: All candidates go to classes for a couple months to gain the base required knowledge in Java, software testing and databases. After a month, candidates get to pick from a more specific track (advanced development, advanced testing or advanced database administration). When the classes are over, students take an exam and then are interviewed based on the track they chose. The interview is pretty straightforward: you are asked about your…  previous experiences (or lack thereof, which was not a problem), familiarity with agile methods, English language fluency.
questions: Why did you choose the track you chose?

details: It was an on-campus placement for M.E people. There was a direct technical interview round and then a HR round.Technical- mostly about strucures, linked lists, const char *p and char const *p difference, big endian and little endian, etc.
